   <div class="prose">
     <h2>Educational support for ADHD</h2>
     <p>There are two main federal laws that require public schools to support students with ADHD. Here is how they compare:</p>
     <h3>Section 504 Plan vs. IEP</h3>
     <div class="overflow-x-auto rounded-xl border border-zinc-200 my-4 not-prose"><table class="w-full text-sm"><thead><tr class="bg-accent-light/50"><th class="py-3 px-4 text-left font-semibold text-zinc-900">Feature</th><th class="py-3 px-4 text-left font-semibold text-zinc-900">Section 504 Plan</th><th class="py-3 px-4 text-left font-semibold text-zinc-900">IEP (Under IDEA)</th></tr></thead><tbody class="text-zinc-600"><tr class="border-t border-zinc-100"><td class="py-2.5 px-4 font-semibold text-zinc-900">Eligibility</td><td class="py-2.5 px-4">Any disability affecting a major life activity</td><td class="py-2.5 px-4">Must adversely affect educational performance</td></tr><tr class="border-t border-zinc-100"><td class="py-2.5 px-4 font-semibold text-zinc-900">Scope</td><td class="py-2.5 px-4">Accommodations for equal access</td><td class="py-2.5 px-4">Specialized instruction, goals, services</td></tr><tr class="border-t border-zinc-100"><td class="py-2.5 px-4 font-semibold text-zinc-900">Common for ADHD</td><td class="py-2.5 px-4"><span class="text-accent-dark font-semibold">Most common</span></td><td class="py-2.5 px-4">When ADHD significantly impacts learning</td></tr></tbody></table></div>
 
     <h3>Common 504 Plan accommodations</h3>
     <p>Students with ADHD typically receive these accommodations through a 504 Plan:</p>
     <h4>In the classroom</h4>
     <ul><li>Preferential seating near teacher, away from distractions</li><li>Frequent breaks during long tasks</li><li>Written instructions in addition to verbal directions</li><li>Noise-reducing headphones during independent work</li><li>Regular check-ins with the teacher to ensure understanding</li></ul>
     <h4>For tests and assignments</h4>
     <ul><li>Extended time on tests and assignments</li><li>Breaking assignments into smaller chunks</li><li>Modified homework -- reduced volume, not reduced difficulty</li></ul>
 
     <h2>IDEA and the "Other Health Impairment" category</h2>
     <p>Under IDEA, ADHD falls under <strong>"Other Health Impairment" (OHI)</strong>. For an IEP, ADHD must <strong>adversely affect educational performance</strong> to require specialized instruction -- not just accommodations.</p>
     <p>Many students with ADHD can manage with a 504 Plan. An IEP is appropriate when ADHD causes significant academic difficulties that require specialized teaching methods, behavior intervention plans, or related services like counseling or occupational therapy.</p>
 
     <h2>How to request a 504 evaluation</h2>
     <ol><li><strong>Write a formal request</strong> to the principal or 504 coordinator -- in writing and dated.</li><li><strong>Include documentation</strong> of ADHD diagnosis from a healthcare provider.</li><li><strong>Describe specific challenges</strong> your child faces at school due to ADHD.</li><li><strong>School must respond</strong> -- legally required to evaluate if they suspect a disability.</li><li><strong>Attend the evaluation meeting</strong> -- you have the right to be present.</li><li><strong>Develop the 504 Plan</strong> with the team if eligible.</li></ol>
 
     <h2>College and post-secondary education</h2>
     <p>In college, IDEA no longer applies. Section 504 and the ADA govern disability services instead:</p>
     <ul><li>Student must self-identify and request accommodations through the disability services office.</li><li>Colleges provide "academic adjustments" under Section 504, not IEPs.</li><li>Documentation requirements vary by institution.</li><li>Common college accommodations: extended test time, note-taking services, priority registration, reduced course load.</li></ul>
